# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alsactide
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] The **adrenocorticotropic hormone receptor** or **ACTH receptor** also known as the **melanocortin receptor 2** or **MC2 receptor** is a type of melanocortin receptor (type 2) which is specific for ACTH.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] A G protein–coupled receptor located on the external cell plasma membrane, it is coupled to Gαs and upregulates levels of cAMP by activating adenylyl cyclase.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] The ACTH receptor plays a role in immune function and glucose metabolism.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] ACTH receptors are the shortest of the melanocortin receptor family and are the smallest known G-coupled receptors.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Both human and bovine ACTH receptors are synthesized as 297 residue long proteins with 81% sequence homology.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] The full length sequence of MC2R includes seven hydrophobic domains that are predicted as transmembrane segments.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] In the third intracellular loop of the receptor a protein kinase A and protein kinase c phosphorylation motifs have been detected.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] ACTH receptors also require the binding of melanocortin-2 receptor accessory protein-1 (MRAP1) without which ACTH receptors cannot bind ACTH.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Without MRAP, the receptor is degraded in the endoplasmic reticulum, but with MRAP, the receptor is glycosylated and expressed on the cell plasma membrane.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] MCR's have both endogenous agonists and antagonists.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] α-MSH and ACTH are both peptides derived from processed POMC, and both activate the other MCR's, but ACTH is the only agonist ligand for MC2R (ACTH receptor).
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] This suggests that there is more protein-related specificity for binding MC2R.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Agouti-related protein and Agouti-signaling protein are antagonist peptides to MC2R.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] ACTH receptor is primarily found in the zona fasciculata of the human adrenal cortex.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Binding of the receptor by ACTH stimulates the production of glucocorticoids (GCs)—by contrast, aldosterone production from the zona glomerulosa is stimulated primarily by angiotensin II.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] ACTH receptors are also expressed in the skin, and in both white and brown adipocytes, and is expressed in greater concentrations when adipose cells differentiate.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] It is well known that levels of corticosterone (CORT, cortisol in humans) secretion demonstrate a circadian rhythm, highly regulated by effects of the suprachiasmatic nucleus, with higher levels in the early evening and lower levels in the morning.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] ACTH levels, ACTH receptor expression, and MRAP1 expression also demonstrate circadian rhythm, with ACTH secretion and MRAP expression highest in the evening, suggesting that MRAP expression is responsible for CORT secretory regulation.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] However, with exposure to constant light, the rhythmic expression of the ACTH receptor and MRAP genes reversed, suggesting ACTH-independent signalling pathways for MRAP and ACTH receptor transcription and expression.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] The ACTH receptor plays a role in glucose metabolism when expressed in white adipose cells.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] When bound to ACTH, a short-term insulin-resistance occurs, and it stimulates lipolysis via hormone sensitive lipase.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Demonstrated in mice, ACTH promotes lipolysis in response to increased energy demand, notably in times of stress.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Lipolytic activity due to melanocortin receptors has been demonstrated in several types of test animals: rats and hamsters primarily respond to ACTH, rabbits respond to alpha and beta MSH's (therefore not using the ACTH receptor), and guinea pigs responding to both ACTH and other MSH's.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] In humans, ACTH has little lipolytic effect on adipose tissue.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] ACTH receptor activation also influences immune function.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Melanocortins, including ACTH, have anti-inflammatory effects which can be exerted via GC-dependent and -independent pathways.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] The GC-dependent pathway activates ACTH receptors to increase levels of cortisol which bind GC receptors.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Via genomic and faster non-genomic pathways, this causes, among other immune responses, a reduction in leukocyte and neutrophil infiltration, cytokine production, especially of cytokine CXCL-1, and increased phagocytosis of apoptotic neutrophils.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] These profound anti-inflammatory effects and the ability to increase GC's are why ACTH therapy is still used today.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] It is often used as treatment for infantile spasms, multiple sclerosis, nephrotic syndrome, gout, ulcerative colitis, Crohn's disease, rheumatoid arthritis, and systemic lupus erythematosus.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] This is problematic long-term and can lead to ACTH-receptor pathway-related side effects including: Cushing's syndrome, fluid retention, glaucoma, and cardiovascular disorders.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Mutations in this receptor cause familial glucocorticoid deficiency (FGD) type 1, in which patients have high levels of serum ACTH and low levels of cortisol.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Mutation of the receptor gene causes 25% of FGD, and mutation on the MRAP gene causes 20% of FGD.
[src:alsactide/acth-receptor] Mutations of ACTH can also contribute to this pathology: mutation of the "message sequence" inhibits cAMP production when bound to the ACTH receptor, and mutation of the "address sequence" inhibits binding to the receptor altogether.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Addison's disease arises when the adrenal gland does not produce sufficient amounts of the steroid hormones cortisol and (sometimes) aldosterone.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] It is an autoimmune disease which affects some genetically predisposed people in whom the body's own immune system has started to target the adrenal glands.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In many adult cases it is unclear what has triggered the onset of this disease, though it sometimes follows tuberculosis.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Causes can include certain medications, sepsis, and bleeding into both adrenal glands.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Addison's disease is generally diagnosed by blood tests, urine tests, and medical imaging.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Treatment involves replacing the absent or low hormones.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This involves taking a synthetic corticosteroid, such as hydrocortisone or fludrocortisone.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] These medications are typically taken orally.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Lifelong, continuous steroid replacement therapy is required, with regular follow-up treatment and monitoring for other health problems which may occur.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] A high-salt diet may also be useful in some people.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] If symptoms worsen, an injection of corticosteroid is recommended (people need to carry a dose with them at all times).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Often, large amounts of intravenous fluids with the sugar dextrose are also required.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] With appropriate treatment, the overall outcome is generally favorable, and most people are able to lead a reasonably normal life.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Without treatment, an adrenal crisis can result in death.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Addison's disease affects about 9 to 14 per 100,000 people in the developed world.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] It occurs most frequently in middle-aged females.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The disease is named after Thomas Addison, a graduate of the University of Edinburgh Medical School, who first described the condition in 1855.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The symptoms of Addison's disease can develop over several months and resemble other medical conditions.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Most common symptoms are caused by low levels of hormones that would normally be produced by the adrenal glands.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Low blood cortisol can cause a variety of symptoms, including fatigue, malaise, muscle and joint pain, reduced appetite, weight loss, and increased sensitivity to cold.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Gastrointestinal symptoms such as nausea, abdominal pain, and vomiting are particularly common.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Low aldosterone can cause affected people to crave salty foods, as well as develop low blood pressure that leads to dizziness upon standing.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In women, low dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) can result in dry and itchy skin, loss of armpit and pubic hair, and reduced sexual drive.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Young children with Addison's disease may have insufficient weight gain and recurrent infections.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Low cortisol also interferes with adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) regulation, sometimes resulting in the darkening of the skin and mucous membranes, particularly in areas exposed to sun or regular friction.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Blood tests in people with Addison's disease often reveal low blood sodium.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Many also have high blood potassium and/or high thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Most people with Addison's disease develop or have a preexisting autoimmune disease.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Particularly common comorbid conditions are autoimmune thyroid disease (40% of people with Addison's), premature ovarian failure (up to 16% of people with Addison's), type 1 diabetes (11%), pernicious anemia (10%), vitiligo (6%) and celiac disease (2%).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The combination of Addison's disease in addition to mucocutaneous candidiasis, hypoparathyroidism, or both, is called autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome type 1.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The presence of Addison's in addition to autoimmune thyroid disease, type 1 diabetes, or both, is called autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome type 2.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] An "adrenal crisis" or "Addisonian crisis" is a constellation of symptoms that indicates severe adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This may be the result of either previously undiagnosed Addison's disease, a disease process suddenly affecting adrenal function (such as adrenal hemorrhage), or an intercurrent problem (e.g., infection, trauma) in someone known to have Addison's disease.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] It is a medical emergency and potentially life-threatening situation requiring immediate emergency treatment.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Causes of adrenal insufficiency can be categorized by the mechanism through which they cause the adrenal glands to produce insufficient cortisol.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This can be due to damage or destruction of the adrenal cortex.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] These deficiencies include glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid hormones as well.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] These are adrenal dysgenesis (the gland has not formed adequately during development), impaired steroidogenesis (the gland is present but is biochemically unable to produce cortisol), or adrenal destruction (disease processes leading to glandular damage).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Darkening (hyperpigmentation) of the skin, including areas not exposed to the sun – characteristic sites of darkening are skin creases (e.g., of the hands), nipple, and the inside of the cheek (buccal mucosa); also, old scars may darken.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This occurs because melanocyte-stimulating hormone (MSH) and ACTH share the same precursor molecule, pro-opiomelanocortin (POMC).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] After production in the anterior pituitary gland, POMC gets cleaved into gamma-MSH, ACTH, and beta-lipotropin.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The subunit ACTH undergoes further cleavage to produce alpha-MSH, the most important MSH for skin pigmentation.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In secondary and tertiary forms of adrenal insufficiency, skin darkening does not occur, as ACTH is not overproduced.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Autoimmune adrenalitis is the most common cause of Addison's disease in the industrialized world as it represents between 68% and 94% of cases.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Autoimmune destruction of the adrenal cortex is caused by an immune reaction against the enzyme 21-hydroxylase (a phenomenon first described in 1992).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This may be isolated or in the context of autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome (APS type 1 or 2), in which other hormone-producing organs, such as the thyroid and pancreas, may also be affected.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] All causes in this category are genetic, and generally very rare.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] These include mutations to the *SF1* transcription factor, congenital adrenal hypoplasia due to *DAX-1* gene mutations and mutations to the ACTH receptor gene (or related genes, such as in the Triple-A or Allgrove syndrome).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] *DAX-1* mutations may cluster in a syndrome with glycerol kinase deficiency with a number of other symptoms when *DAX-1* is deleted together with a number of other genes.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] To form cortisol, the adrenal gland requires cholesterol, which is then converted biochemically into steroid hormones.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Interruptions in the delivery of cholesterol include Smith–Lemli–Opitz syndrome and abetalipoproteinemia.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Of the synthesis problems, congenital adrenal hyperplasia is the most common (in various forms: 21-hydroxylase, 17α-hydroxylase, 11β-hydroxylase and 3β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase), lipoid CAH due to deficiency of StAR and mitochondrial DNA mutations.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Some medications interfere with steroid synthesis enzymes (e.g., ketoconazole), while others accelerate the normal breakdown of hormones by the liver (e.g., rifampicin, phenytoin).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In suspected cases of Addison's disease, demonstration of low adrenal hormone levels even after appropriate stimulation (called the ACTH stimulation test or synacthen test) with synthetic pituitary ACTH hormone tetracosactide is needed for the diagnosis.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Two tests are performed, the short and the long test.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Dexamethasone does not cross-react with the assay and can be administered concomitantly during testing.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The short test compares blood cortisol levels before and after 250 micrograms of tetracosactide (intramuscular or intravenous) is given.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] If one hour later, plasma cortisol exceeds 170 nmol/L and has risen by at least 330 nmol/L to at least 690 nmol/L, adrenal failure is excluded.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] If the short test is abnormal, the long test is used to differentiate between primary adrenal insufficiency and secondary adrenocortical insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The long test uses 1 mg tetracosactide (intramuscular).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Blood is taken 1, 4, 8, and 24 hours later.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Normal plasma cortisol level should reach 1,000 nmol/L by 4 hours.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In primary Addison's disease, the cortisol level is reduced at all stages, whereas in secondary corticoadrenal insufficiency, a delayed but normal response is seen.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Other tests may be performed to distinguish between various causes of hypoadrenalism, including renin and adrenocorticotropic hormone levels, as well as medical imaging – usually in the form of ultrasound, computed tomography or magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Adrenoleukodystrophy, and the milder form, adrenomyeloneuropathy, cause adrenal insufficiency combined with neurological symptoms.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] These diseases are estimated to be the cause of adrenal insufficiency in about 35% of diagnosed males with idiopathic Addison's disease and should be considered in the differential diagnosis of any male with adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Diagnosis is made by a blood test to detect very long-chain fatty acids.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Treatment for Addison's disease involves replacing the missing cortisol, sometimes in the form of hydrocortisone tablets, or prednisone tablets in a dosing regimen that mimics the physiological concentrations of cortisol.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Alternatively, one-quarter as much prednisolone may be used for equal glucocorticoid effect as hydrocortisone.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In addition, many people require fludrocortisone as a replacement for the missing aldosterone.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] People with Addison's are often advised to carry information on them (e.g., in the form of a MedicAlert bracelet or information card) for the attention of emergency medical services personnel who might need to attend to their needs.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] A needle, syringe, and injectable form of cortisol are also recommended to be carried for emergencies.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] People with Addison's disease are advised to increase their medication during periods of illness or when undergoing surgery or dental treatment.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Immediate medical attention is needed when severe infections, vomiting, or diarrhea occur, as these conditions can precipitate an Addisonian crisis.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] A person who is vomiting may require injections of hydrocortisone, instead.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Those with low aldosterone levels may also benefit from a high-sodium diet.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] It may also be beneficial for the people with Addison's disease to increase their dietary intake of calcium and vitamin D.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] High dosages of corticosteroids are linked to osteoporosis so these may be necessary for bone health.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Sources of calcium include dairy products, leafy greens, and fortified flours among many others.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Vitamin D can be obtained through the sun, oily fish, red meat, and egg yolks among many others.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Though there are many sources to obtain vitamin D through diet, supplements are also an option.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Standard therapy involves intravenous injections of glucocorticoids and large volumes of intravenous saline solution with dextrose (glucose).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This treatment usually brings rapid improvement.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] If intravenous access is not immediately available, intramuscular injection of glucocorticoids can be used.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] When the person is capable of swallowing fluids and medications by mouth, the amount of glucocorticoids is decreased until a maintenance dose is reached.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] If aldosterone is deficient, maintenance therapy also includes oral doses of fludrocortisone acetate.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Outcomes are typically good when treated.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Most people can expect to live relatively normal lives.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Someone with the disease should be observant of symptoms of an "Addison's crisis" while the body is strained, as in rigorous exercise or being sick, the latter often needing emergency treatment with intravenous injections to treat the crisis.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Individuals with Addison's disease have more than a doubled mortality rate.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Furthermore, individuals with Addison's disease and diabetes mellitus have an almost four-fold increase in mortality compared to individuals with only diabetes.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The risk ratio for cause mortality in males and females is 2.19 and 2.86, respectively.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Death for individuals with Addison's disease often occurs due to cardiovascular disease, infectious disease, and malignant tumors, among other possibilities.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Recent studies indicate that individuals with Addison's disease may have an increased risk of osteoporotic fractures and higher rates of work loss, including sick leave and disability pension.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The frequency rate of Addison's disease in the human population is sometimes estimated at one in 100,000.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Addison's can affect persons of any age, sex, or ethnicity, but it typically presents in adults between 30 and 50 years of age.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Research has shown no significant predispositions based on ethnicity.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] About 70% of Addison's disease diagnoses occur due to autoimmune reactions, which cause damage to the adrenal cortex.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Addison's disease is named after Thomas Addison, the British physician who first described the condition in *On the Constitutional and Local Effects of Disease of the Suprarenal Capsules* (1855).
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] He originally described it as "melasma suprarenale", but later physicians gave it the medical eponym "Addison's disease" in recognition of Addison's discovery.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] While the six patients examined by Addison in 1855 all had adrenal tuberculosis, the term "Addison's disease" does not imply an underlying disease process.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The condition was initially considered a form of anemia associated with the adrenal glands.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Because little was known at the time about the adrenal glands (then called "Supra-Renal Capsules"), Addison's monograph describing the condition was an isolated insight.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] As the adrenal function became better known, Addison's monograph became known as an important medical contribution and a classic example of careful medical observation.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Tuberculosis used to be a major cause of Addison's disease and acute adrenal failure worldwide.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] It remains a leading cause in developing countries today.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Kennedy (1917–1963) suffered from complications of Addison's disease throughout his life, including during his presidency, resulting in fatigue and hyperpigmentation of the face.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] He is possibly the most famous known case.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The novelist Jane Austen, whose own description of her illness included her turning "every wrong colour", was suggested to have suffered from Addison's by medical historian Zachary Cope.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Hypoadrenocorticism is uncommon in dogs, and rare in cats, with less than 40 known feline cases worldwide, since first documented in 1983.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Individual cases have been reported in a grey seal, a red panda, a flying fox, and a sloth.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In dogs, hypoadrenocorticism has been diagnosed in many breeds.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Vague symptoms, which wax and wane, can cause delay in recognition of the presence of the disease.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Female dogs appear more affected than male dogs, though this may not be the case in all breeds.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] The disease is most often diagnosed in dogs that are young to middle-aged, but it can occur at any age from 4 months to 14 years.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Treatment of hypoadrenocorticism must replace the hormones (cortisol and aldosterone) which the dog cannot produce itself.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This is achieved either by daily treatment with fludrocortisone, or monthly injections with desoxycorticosterone pivalate (DOCP) and daily treatment with a glucocorticoid, such as prednisone.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Several follow-up blood tests are required so the dose can be adjusted until the dog is receiving the correct amount of treatment, because the medications used in the therapy of hypoadrenocorticism can cause excessive thirst and urination if not prescribed at the lowest effective dose.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] In anticipation of stressful situations, such as staying in a boarding kennel, dogs require an increased dose of prednisone.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Lifelong treatment is required, but the prognosis for dogs with hypoadrenocorticism is very good.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Michigan State University has conducted a study that explores the process of getting to the lowest effective dose safely.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] This must be done slowly over time, so that crisis does not occur.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Medications should never be suddenly stopped, as this will cause severe medical issues quickly.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] Hypoadrenocorticism can also occur in cats but is extremely rare.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] It is usually caused by an immune reaction, resulting in adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/addison-s-disease] An ACTH stimulation test is used to diagnosis the condition.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Adrenal insufficiency can be caused by dysfunction of the adrenal gland itself, whether by destruction (e.g., Addison's disease), failure of development (e.g., adrenal dysgenesis), or enzyme deficiency (e.g., congenital adrenal hyperplasia).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Adrenal insufficiency can also occur when the pituitary gland or the hypothalamus do not produce adequate amounts of the hormones that assist in regulating adrenal function.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] This is called secondary adrenal insufficiency (when caused by lack of production of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) in the pituitary gland) or tertiary adrenal insufficiency (when caused by lack of corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) in the hypothalamus).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] There are three major types of adrenal insufficiency, depending on the affected organ.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Signs and symptoms include: hypoglycemia, hyperpigmentation, dehydration, weight loss, and disorientation.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Additional signs and symptoms include weakness, tiredness, dizziness, low blood pressure that falls further when standing (orthostatic hypotension), cardiovascular collapse, muscle aches, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] These problems may develop gradually and insidiously.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Addison's disease can present with tanning of the skin that may be patchy or even all over the body.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Characteristic sites of tanning are skin creases (e.g., of the hands) and the inside of the cheek (buccal mucosa).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Goitre and vitiligo may also be present.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Hyponatremia is a sign of secondary insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] When functioning normally, the adrenal glands secrete glucocorticoids (primarily cortisol) in the *zona fasciculata* and mineralocorticoids (primarily aldosterone) in the *zona glomerulosa* to regulate metabolism, blood pressure, and electrolyte balance.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Adrenal hormone production is controlled by the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis, in which the hypothalamus produces corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH), which stimulates the pituitary gland to produce adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), which stimulates the adrenal gland to produce cortisol.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] High levels of cortisol inhibit the production of both CRH and ACTH, forming a negative feedback loop.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The types of adrenal insufficiency thus refer to the level of the axis in which the dysfunction originates: primary, secondary, and tertiary for adrenal glands, pituitary gland, and hypothalamus, respectively.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] In adrenal insufficiency, cortisol production is deficient, which may be accompanied by a deficiency in aldosterone production (predominantly in primary adrenal insufficiency).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Depending on the cause and type of adrenal insufficiency, the mechanism of the disease differs.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Generally, the symptoms manifest through the systemic effects of cortisol and aldosterone.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] In secondary and tertiary adrenal insufficiency, there is no effect on the production of aldosterone within the *zona glomerulosa* as this process is regulated by the renin–angiotensin–aldosterone system (RAAS), not ACTH.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Adrenal insufficiency can also affect the *zona reticularis* and disrupt production of androgens, which are precursors to testosterone and estrogen.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] This leads to a deficiency of sex hormones and can contribute to symptoms of depression and menstrual irregularities.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Cortisol increases blood sugar by inducing gluconeogenesis (glucose production) in the liver, lipolysis (fat breakdown) in adipose tissue, and proteolysis (muscle breakdown) in muscle while increasing glucagon secretion and decreasing insulin secretion in the pancreas.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Overall, these actions cause the body to use fat stores and muscle for energy.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Deficiency results in hypoglycemia, with associated nausea, vomiting, fatigue, and weakness.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Cortisol potentiates the effectiveness of angiotensin II and catecholamines such as norepinephrine in vasoconstriction.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Thus, a deficiency can contribute to hypotension, though this effect is most pronounced in mineralocorticoid deficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] In primary adrenal insufficiency, the lack of negative feedback from cortisol leads to increased production of CRH and ACTH.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] ACTH is derived from pro-opiomelanocortin (POMC), which is cleaved into ACTH as well as α-MSH, which regulates production of melanin in the skin.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The overproduction of α-MSH leads to the characteristic hyperpigmentation of Addison's disease.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Although the production of aldosterone occurs within the adrenal cortex, it is not induced by adrenocorticotropic (ACTH); instead, it is regulated by the renin–angiotensin–aldosterone system (RAAS).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Renin production in the juxtaglomerular cells of the kidney is induced by decreased arterial blood pressure, decreased sodium content in the distal convoluted tubule, and increased sympathetic tone.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Renin initiates the downstream sequence of cleavage of angiotensinogen to angiotensin I to angiotensin II, in which angiotensin II stimulates aldosterone production in the *zona glomerulosa*.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Thus, dysfunction of the pituitary gland or the hypothalamus does not affect the production of aldosterone.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] However, in primary adrenal insufficiency, damage to the adrenal cortex (e.g. autoimmune adrenalitis a.k.a.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Addison's disease) can lead to destruction of the *zona glomerulosa* and therefore a loss of aldosterone production.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Aldosterone acts on mineralocorticoid receptors on epithelial cells lining the distal convoluted tubule, activating epithelial sodium channels (ENaC) and the Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase pump.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] This results in the absorption of sodium (with resulting retention of fluid) and the excretion of potassium.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Deficiency of aldosterone leads to urinary loss of sodium and effective circulating volume, as well as retention of potassium.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] This can cause hypotension (in severe cases, shock), dizziness (from orthostatic hypotension), dehydration, and salt craving.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Unlike mineralocorticoid deficiency, glucocorticoid deficiency does not cause a negative sodium balance (in fact, a positive sodium balance may occur).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Causes of acute adrenal insufficiency are mainly sudden withdrawal of long-term corticosteroid therapy, Waterhouse–Friderichsen syndrome, and stress in people with underlying chronic adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The latter is termed critical illness–related corticosteroid insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] For chronic adrenal insufficiency, the major contributors are autoimmune adrenalitis (Addison's Disease), tuberculosis, AIDS, and metastatic disease.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Minor causes of chronic adrenal insufficiency are systemic amyloidosis, fungal infections, hemochromatosis, and sarcoidosis.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] These are adrenal destruction (disease processes leading to glandular damage), impaired steroidogenesis (the gland is present but is biochemically unable to produce cortisol), or adrenal dysgenesis (the gland has not formed adequately during development).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Autoimmune adrenalitis (Addison's disease) is the most common cause of primary adrenal insufficiency in the industrialised world, causing 80–90% of cases since 1950.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Autoimmune adrenalitis may be part of type 2 autoimmune polyglandular syndrome, which can include type 1 diabetes, hyperthyroidism, and autoimmune thyroid disease (also known as autoimmune thyroiditis, Hashimoto's thyroiditis, and Hashimoto's disease).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Hypogonadism may also present with this syndrome.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Other diseases that are more common in people with autoimmune adrenalitis include premature ovarian failure, celiac disease, and autoimmune gastritis with pernicious anemia.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Adrenal destruction is a feature of adrenoleukodystrophy (ALD).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Some medications interfere with steroid synthesis enzymes (e.g. ketoconazole), while others accelerate the normal breakdown of hormones by the liver (e.g. rifampicin, phenytoin).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The same can occur with masses in the hypothalamus (tertiary adrenal insufficiency).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Use of high-dose steroids for more than a week begins to produce suppression of the person's adrenal glands because the exogenous glucocorticoids suppress release of hypothalamic corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) and pituitary adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] With prolonged suppression, the adrenal glands atrophy (physically shrink), and can take months to recover full function after discontinuation of the exogenous glucocorticoid.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] During this recovery time, the person is vulnerable to adrenal insufficiency during times of stress, such as illness, due to both adrenal atrophy and suppression of CRH and ACTH release.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Use of steroids joint injections may also result in adrenal suppression after discontinuation.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] All causes in this category are genetic and generally very rare.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] These include mutations to the *SF1* transcription factor, congenital adrenal hypoplasia due to *DAX-1* gene mutations and mutations to the ACTH receptor gene (or related genes, such as in the Triple A or Allgrove syndrome).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The first step of diagnosing adrenal insufficiency is confirming inappropriately low cortisol secretion.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] This is followed by determining the origin of dysfunction (adrenal glands, pituitary gland, or hypothalamus) and therefore the type of adrenal insufficiency (primary, secondary, or tertiary).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] After narrowing down the source, further testing can elucidate the cause of insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] If a patient is suspected to be experiencing an acute adrenal crisis, immediate treatment with IV corticosteroids is imperative and should not be delayed for any testing, as the patient's health can deteriorate rapidly and result in death without replacing the corticosteroids.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Dexamethasone should be used as the corticosteroid of choice in these cases as it is the only corticosteroid that will not affect diagnostic test results.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] To confirm inappropriately low cortisol secretion, testing may include baseline morning cortisol level in the blood or morning cortisol level in the saliva.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Cortisol levels typically peak in the morning; thus, low values indicate true adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Urinary free cortisol can also be measured, but is not necessary for diagnosis.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] To determine the origin of dysfunction, the ACTH stimulation test is the best initial test as it can differentiate between primary and secondary adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] If cortisol levels remain low following ACTH stimulation, then the diagnosis is primary adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] If cortisol levels increase following ACTH stimulation, then the diagnosis is either secondary or tertiary adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The corticotropin-releasing hormone test can then differentiate between secondary and tertiary adrenal insufficiency.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Additional testing can include basal plasma ACTH, renin, and aldosterone concentrations, as well as a blood chemistry panel to check for electrolyte imbalances.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Depending on the type of adrenal insufficiency, there are several possible causes and therefore many different avenues of testing (see Causes above).
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] For primary adrenal insufficiency, the most common cause is autoimmune adrenalitis (Addison's disease); therefore, 21-hydroxylase autoantibodies should be checked.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Structural abnormalities of the adrenal glands can be detected on CT imaging.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] For secondary and tertiary adrenal insufficiency, an MRI of the brain can be obtained to detect structural abnormalities such as masses, metastasis, hemorrhage, infarction, or infection.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] In general, the treatment of adrenal insufficiency requires replacement of deficient hormones, as well as treatment of any underlying cause.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] All types of adrenal insufficiency will require glucocorticoid repletion.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Many cases (typically, primary adrenal insufficiency) will also require mineralocorticoid repletion.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] In rarer cases, repletion of androgens may also be indicated, typically in female patients with mood disturbances and changes in well-being.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Primary adrenal insufficiency predisposes to a higher risk of death, mostly due to infection, cardiovascular disease, and adrenal crisis.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] Delayed diagnosis can impair quality of life, and lack of treatment brings high mortality.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] However, with proper diagnosis, monitoring, and treatment, people with adrenal insufficiency can live normally.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The most common cause of primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison's disease) overall is autoimmune adrenalitis.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] The prevalence of Addison's disease ranges from 5 to 221 per million in different countries.
[src:alsactide/adrenal-insufficiency] In children, congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH) is the most common cause of adrenal insufficiency, with an incidence of 1 in 14,200 live births.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] The form that is purified from pig pituitary glands is known as **corticotropin** is a medication and naturally occurring polypeptide tropic hormone produced and secreted by the anterior pituitary gland.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] The form that is made synthetically is **tetracosactide**, also known as **synacthen**, **tetracosactrin** and **cosyntropin**.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] It consists of the first 24 (of a total of 39) amino acids of ACTH and retains full function of the parent peptide.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Tetracosactide stimulates the release of corticosteroids such as cortisol from the adrenal glands, and is used for the ACTH stimulation test to assess adrenal gland function.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Both corticotropin and tetracosactide have been used for diagnostic purposes to determine adrenocortical insufficiency, particularly in Addison's disease, via the ACTH stimulation test.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] However, as of 2015 the US label for corticotropin does not include diagnostic use.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Both corticotropin and tetracosactide have been used for therapeutic purposes.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] In the US the tetracosactide label is limited to diagnosis but the UK label provides for therapeutic uses.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] The same contraindications that were applied in the UK for diagnostic use of tetracosactide, apply for therapeutic use of both tetracosactide and corticotropin in the US and UK.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] The label also notes that people taking corticotropin for immunosuppression should not be given live vaccines.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] People taking corticotropin or tetracosactide are more likely to get infections, and are at risk of hypothalamic-pituitary-axis (HPA) suppression and Cushing's syndrome.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] In the normal situation, ACTH is released from the pituitary gland at the base of the brain.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] It acts on the adrenal glands to stimulate the production of steroid hormones (glucocorticoids).
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] If the adrenal glands are healthy, a single injection of tetracosactide results in a rise in blood cortisol concentrations in 30 minutes.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] If the adrenal glands appear not to be working then tetracosactide injection can be given to check whether the problem is due to diseased or damaged adrenals or due to lack of pituitary ACTH.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] The synthetic form consists of the first 24 (of a total of 39) amino acids of ACTH and retains full function of the parent peptide.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Synthetic forms were created as a replacement for the animal-derived products.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] As of 2007, it was widely reported that tetracosactide had been used as an illegal performance-enhancing drug by professional cyclists.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] It is known to be used as a doping agent to increase the secretion of glucocorticoids by adrenal glands.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Mallinckrodt acquired the US rights to the animal-derived form via its acquisition of Questcor Pharmaceuticals in 2014.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] When Questcor acquired the drug in 2001 it sold for $40 a vial; within a year of the acquisition Questcor raised the price of the drug to $1,500 per vial and to $28,000 by 2013.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] In 2013, Questcor acquired the US rights to a competing product, Synacthen Depot, from Novartis.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] In 2014 Mallinckrodt raised the price of Acthar further to $34,000.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] According to Kaiser Health News, Mallinckrodt responded by increasing its Congressional lobbying to $610,000, and its contributions to Congress members to $44,000, in the first quarter of 2017.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] In Canada, Synacthen Depot's pricing increased by 2000% in 2015, causing some provincial single payer authorities to delist the drug from funded medications.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] The increase in the drug's price came after Mallinckrodt acquired Questcor and its drug portfolio, which included the worldwide rights to Synacthen Depot.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Prior to the price increase, Mallinckrodt claims that the drug was manufactured at a loss.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Some have claimed that the price increase is abusive.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] The drug had been priced at $33 but rose to $680 per vial.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] As an off-patent pharmaceutical, a similar drug, differing in formulation, available in Europe, made by a different manufacturer, sells for $8 per vial.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Acthar gel has been proposed as a therapy to treat refractory autoimmune diseases and refractory nephrotic syndrome due to a variety of glomerular diseases.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone-medication] Both versions of the hormone are also used to perform the ACTH stimulation test to diagnose hypoadrenocorticism in dogs and sometimes cats.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] Conversely, chronically elevated ACTH levels occur in primary adrenal insufficiency (e.g.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] Addison's disease) when adrenal gland production of cortisol is chronically deficient.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] In Cushing's disease, a pituitary tumor leads to excessive production of ACTH, which stimulates the adrenal cortex to produce high levels of cortisol.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] POMC, ACTH and β-lipotropin are secreted from corticotropic cells in the anterior lobe (or adenohypophysis) of the pituitary gland in response to the hormone corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) released by the hypothalamus.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] The pre-pro-opiomelanocortin (Pre-POMC) is the precursor of POMC, its cleavage forms POMC.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] ACTH, on the other hand, is produced from the cleavage of POMC.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] In order to regulate the secretion of ACTH, many substances secreted within this axis exhibit slow/intermediate and fast feedback-loop activity.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] Glucocorticoids secreted from the adrenal cortex work to inhibit CRH secretion by the hypothalamus, which in turn decreases anterior pituitary secretion of ACTH.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] Glucocorticoids may also inhibit the rates of POMC gene transcription and peptide synthesis.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] The latter is an example of a slow feedback loop, which works on the order of hours to days, whereas the former works on the order of minutes.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] The half-life of ACTH in human blood is reported to be between ten and 30 minutes.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] ACTH consists of 39 amino acids, the first 13 of which (counting from the N-terminus) may be cleaved to form α-melanocyte-stimulating hormones (α-MSH) (this common structure is responsible for excessively tanned skin in Addison's disease).
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] After a short period of time, ACTH is cleaved into α-melanocyte-stimulating hormone (α-MSH) and CLIP, a peptide with unknown activity in humans.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] In the human body, total weight ACTH is 4540 Da.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] ACTH stimulates secretion of glucocorticoid steroid hormones from adrenal cortex cells, especially in the zona fasciculata of the adrenal glands.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] ACTH acts by binding to cell surface ACTH receptors, which are located primarily on adrenocortical cells of the adrenal cortex.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] The ACTH receptor is a seven-membrane-spanning G protein-coupled receptor.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] Upon ligand binding, the receptor undergoes conformation changes that stimulate the enzyme adenylyl cyclase, which leads to an increase in intracellular cAMP and subsequent activation of protein kinase A.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] ACTH influences steroid hormone secretion by both rapid short-term mechanisms that take place within minutes and slower long-term actions.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] The rapid actions of ACTH include stimulation of cholesterol delivery to the mitochondria where the P450scc enzyme is located.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] P450scc catalyzes the first step of steroidogenesis that is cleavage of the side-chain of cholesterol.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] ACTH also stimulates lipoprotein uptake into cortical cells.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] This increases the bioavailability of cholesterol in the cells of the adrenal cortex.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] The long term actions of ACTH include stimulation of the transcription of the genes coding for steroidogenic enzymes, especially P450scc, steroid 11β-hydroxylase, and their associated electron transfer proteins.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] This effect is observed over several hours.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] In addition to steroidogenic enzymes, ACTH also enhances transcription of mitochondrial genes that encode for subunits of mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation systems.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] These actions are probably necessary to supply the enhanced energy needs of adrenocortical cells stimulated by ACTH.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] As indicated above, ACTH is a cleavage product of the pro-hormone, proopiomelanocortin (POMC), which also produces other hormones including α-MSH that stimulates the production of melanin.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] A family of related receptors mediates the actions of these hormones, the MCR, or melanocortin receptor family.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] These are mainly not associated with the pituitary-adrenal axis.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] While it has a crucial function in regulating the adrenal glands, it is also expressed elsewhere in the body, specifically in the osteoblast, which is responsible for making new bone, a continual and highly regulated process in the bodies of air-breathing vertebrates.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] The functional expression of MC2R on the osteoblast was discovered by Isales et alia in 2005.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] Since that time, it has been demonstrated that the response of bone forming cells to ACTH includes production of VEGF, as it does in the adrenal.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] This response might be important in maintaining osteoblast survival under some conditions.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] If this is physiologically important, it probably functions in conditions with short-period or intermittent ACTH signaling, since with continual exposure of osteoblasts to ACTH, the effect was lost in a few hours.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] While working on her dissertation, Evelyn M.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] Anderson co-discovered ACTH with James Bertram Collip and David Landsborough Thomson and, in a paper published in 1933, explained its function in the body.
[src:alsactide/adrenocorticotropic-hormone] An active synthetic form of ACTH, consisting of the first 23 amino acids of native ACTH, was first made by Klaus Hofmann at the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) considers it to be a first-in-class medication.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] In the European Union, afamelanotide is indicated for the prevention of phototoxicity in adults with erythropoietic protoporphyria.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] In the United States, afamelanotide is indicated for increasing pain-free light exposure in adults with a history of reactions to light (phototoxicity) from erythropoietic protoporphyria.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Very common adverse effects include nausea and headache (may affect more than 10% of people).
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Afamelanotide is a synthetic tridecapeptide and a structural analogue of α-melanocyte stimulating hormone (α-MSH).
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] It is a melanocortin receptor agonist and binds predominantly to the MC1 receptor.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Its binding lasts longer than that of α-MSH.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] This results in part from afamelanotide's resistance to immediate degradation by serum or proteolytic enzymes.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] It is thought to cause skin darkening by binding to the MC1 receptor which in turn drives melanogenesis.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] It has a short half-life of approximately 30 minutes.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] After administration with implantation into the skin, the majority of the drug is released within two days, with 90% released by the fifth day.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] By the tenth day, no drug is detectable in plasma.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Drug distribution, metabolism and excretion were not understood as of 2017.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Afamelanotide has the amino acid sequence; Ac-Ser-Tyr-Ser-Nle-Glu-His-D-Phe-Arg-Trp-Gly-Lys-Pro-Val-NH2.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] It is also known as [Nle4,D-Phe7]-α-MSH, which is abbreviated to NDP-MSH or NDP-α-MSH.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Afamelanotide is the international nonproprietary name.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] α-MSH was first isolated in the 1950s and its primary structure determined.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] By the 1960s, its role in promoting melanin diffusion was understood.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] In the 1980s, the University of Arizona synthesised more potent analogs of a-MSH, including afamelanotide.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Afamelanotide was initially named melano-tan (or melanotan-I) due to its ability to tan skin with minimal sun exposure.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Following initial development at the University of Arizona as a sunless tanning agent, the Australian company Clinuvel conducted further clinical trials in that and other indications, and brought the drug to market in the European Union, the United States, and Australia.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] To pursue the tanning agent, melanotan-I was licensed by Competitive Technologies, a technology transfer company operating on behalf of University of Arizona, to an Australian startup called Epitan, which changed its name to Clinuvel in 2006.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Early clinical trials showed that the peptide had to be injected about ten times a day due to its short half-life, so the company collaborated with Southern Research in the US to develop a depot formulation that would be injected under the skin, and release the peptide slowly.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Multiple studies on the clinical effects of afamelanotide were conducted.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] According to ClinicalTrials.gov, Clinuvel sponsored several trials between 2007 and 2011 to explore its effects on erythropoietic protoporphyria, vitiligo, polymorphous light eruption, solar urticaria and acne vulgaris.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Additionally, one trial aimed to assess its role in preventing actinic keratosis in organ transplant recipients.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Further trials were pursued for the first two conditions, while results for the latter three were not published.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Following the initial trials, research efforts centered on erythropoietic protoporphyria, and due to the epidemiology of the condition.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Clinuvel secured orphan drug for afamelanotide in both the US and the EU by 2010.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] The first approval of afamelanotide came in May 2010 from the Italian Medicines Agency (AIFA, or Agenzia Italiana del Farmaco), followed by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) in January 2015.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Both approvals were for the treatment of erythropoietic protoporphyria.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) granted approval in October 2019 for the use of afamelanotide as a medication to alleviate pain caused by sun exposure in individuals with erythropoietic protoporphyria.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] This decision was largely based on three trials involving 244 adults aged 18–74 across 22 sites in the US and Europe, which had a focus on pain-free hours in sunlight, outdoor hours under varying light conditions, and side effects.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Between 2022 and 2023, trials were outlined to study the effects of afamelanotide on xeroderma pigmentosum and variegate porphyria, along with two additional trials exploring its impact on vitiligo.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] According to the register, as of April 2025, most of these trials are currently in the recruitment phase.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] A number of products are sold online and in gyms and beauty salons as "melanotan" or "melanotan-1" which discuss afamelanotide in their marketing.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Without a prescription, these drugs are not legally sold in many jurisdictions and are potentially dangerous.
[src:alsactide/afamelanotide] Starting in 2007, health agencies in various countries began issuing warnings against their use.
[src:alsactide/atc-code-v04] Codes for veterinary use (ATCvet codes) can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the human ATC code: for example, **QV04**.
[src:alsactide/atc-code-v04] ATCvet codes without corresponding human ATC codes are cited with the leading Q in the following list.
[src:alsactide/atc-code-v04] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
